import math
p = stats.poisson.cdf(k=20100, mu=20000)
sigma = stats.norm.ppf(p)
print(sigma)
print(100/math.sqrt(20000))

0.7112259282313185
0.7071067811865475

N_higgs is the difference between the mean and measurement. sqrt(N_qcd) is the standard deviation of the Poisson distribution. With this in mind, the sigma value that we calculated (0.711) should be very similar to the equation since the difference of mean and measurement over standard deviation is the Z- score (0.707), and since Poisson is essentially a type of gaussian, sigma and z-score should be very similar.

since Higgs doesn't have any signal with mass above 143, it's fair to assume to get rid of all qcd background with a mass of about 143. And from the data distribution, we can see the region with Higgs pick is around the mass of 115 - 135. So I set my lower bound within this region and do a for loop and found the lower bound with a mass of 123 produces the largest sigma.

In [25]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(40, 40))

rows = 2
columns = 2
n = 0
cuts = [[masscut1, masscut2], [d2cut1, d2cut2], [t21cut1, t21cut2], [t2cut1, t2cut2]]


for x in ['mass', 'd2', 't21', 't2']:
    mask1 = (higgs_dict[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (higgs_dict[x] < cuts[n][1])
    mask2 = (qcd_dict[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (qcd_dict[x] < cuts[n][1])
    mask3 = (readHigh[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (readHigh[x] < cuts[n][1])
    
    higgsN = higgs_dict[x][mask1].shape[0]
    qcdN = qcd_dict[x][mask2].shape[0]
    highLumiN = readHigh[x][mask3].shape[0]
    total = higgs_dict[x][mask1].append(qcd_dict[x][mask2])

    A = np.array([[higgsN,qcdN], [1,-1/200]])
    B = np.array([highLumiN, 0])
    Ans = np.linalg.inv(A).dot(B)

    higgsWei = np.full(higgsN, [Ans[0]])
    qcdWei = np.full(qcdN, [Ans[1]])
    n = n + 1
    fig.add_subplot(rows, columns, n)
    
    plt.hist(total, bins = 50, weights = np.append(higgsWei, qcdWei), alpha = 0.5)
    plt.hist(readHigh[x][mask3], bins = 50, alpha = 0.5)

    plt.legend(["simulation data", "observed highLumi data"], fontsize = 30)
    plt.title("obs data and simulation with even selection on " + str(x), fontsize = 30)
    plt.xlabel(str(x), fontsize = 30)
    plt.ylabel("counts", fontsize = 30)  
    plt.yscale('log')
In [56]:
qcdRatio = (n_qcd*5)/100000
print(qcdRatio)
expectedHighLumiQcd = readHigh.shape[0] * qcdRatio
print(expectedHighLumiQcd)

mask = (readHigh['mass'] > masscut1) & (readHigh['mass'] < masscut2)\
& (readHigh['d2'] > d2cut1) & (readHigh['d2'] < d2cut2)\
& (readHigh['t21'] > t21cut1) & (readHigh['t21'] < t21cut2)\
& (readHigh['t2'] > t2cut1) & (readHigh['t2'] < t2cut2)\

n_highLumi = readHigh[mask].shape[0]
print(n_highLumi)

p = stats.poisson.cdf(k=n_highLumi, mu=expectedHighLumiQcd)
sigma = stats.norm.ppf(p)
print(sigma)

0.00716
288.86304
406
6.5263171287916295

To compare the observed significance and expectation, I first find the percentage of the qcd that passed the cuts (0.71%) and use it as the reference of the number of High luminosity data that would pass the cut, which is 289, and this is the mean of the Poisson distribution. To find the measurement, I then used the same cuts to the high luminosity data and found the number of events passed to be 406. Applied this 289 as the mean and 406 as our measurement and we can find the observed significance to be 6.5 sigma, which is higher than the expected significance (4.6 sigma) that we found from problem 7.4.

rows = 2
columns = 2
n = 0
cuts = [[masscut1, masscut2], [d2cut1, d2cut2], [t21cut1, t21cut2], [t2cut1, t2cut2]]


for x in ['mass', 'd2', 't21', 't2']:
    mask1 = (higgs_dict[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (higgs_dict[x] < cuts[n][1])
    mask2 = (qcd_dict[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (qcd_dict[x] < cuts[n][1])
    mask3 = (readLow[x] > cuts[n][0]) & (readLow[x] < cuts[n][1])
    
    higgsN = higgs_dict[x][mask1].shape[0]
    qcdN = qcd_dict[x][mask2].shape[0]
    lowLumiN = readLow[x][mask3].shape[0]
    total = higgs_dict[x][mask1].append(qcd_dict[x][mask2])

    A = np.array([[higgsN,qcdN], [1,-1/200]])
    B = np.array([lowLumiN, 0])
    Ans = np.linalg.inv(A).dot(B)

    higgsWei = np.full(higgsN, [Ans[0]])
    qcdWei = np.full(qcdN, [Ans[1]])
    n = n + 1
    fig.add_subplot(rows, columns, n)
    
    plt.hist(total, bins = 50, weights = np.append(higgsWei, qcdWei), alpha = 0.5)
    plt.hist(readLow[x][mask3], bins = 50, alpha = 0.5)

    plt.legend(["simulation data", "observed lowLumi data"], fontsize = 30)
    plt.title("obs data and simulation with even selection on " + str(x), fontsize = 30)
    plt.xlabel(str(x), fontsize = 30)
    plt.ylabel("counts", fontsize = 30)  
    plt.yscale('log')

Similar to the steps above, I first find the percentage of the qcd that passed the cuts (0.71%) and use it as the reference of the number of Low luminosity data that would pass the cut, which is 29, and this is the mean of the Poisson distribution. To find the measurement, I applied the same cuts to the low luminosity data and found the number of events passed to be 45. I then used 29 as the mean and 45 as our measurement and we can find the observed significance to be 2.8 sigma, which is lower than the expected significance.
